One solution is to wrap it in an initializer function, then call that initializer function instead:

    def rec(I: List[int]) -&gt; List[int]:
        ....(new_lst is edited)

        rec(new_lst)
        return new_lst

    def startrec(I: List[int]) -&gt; List[int]:
        return rec(I[:])

The functions `add`, `subtract`, `divide`, `multiply` are not static functions, so you can&#39;t use the format: `class_name::function_name` to call them. Replace the call to each one of them with `this-&gt;function_name(...)` or just `function_name(...)` (from the current object) to use them.

Alternatively, you can make them static by changing their declarations to: `static ... function_name(...)`, and then call them like you did.

----------------
&lt;h2&gt;Why `static`?&lt;/h2&gt;
`static` means that the method belong to the class, and no to a specific object instance of it. It seems like your `rational` class&#39;s operations functions (add, substruct, etc...) don&#39;t need any `rational` class specific object members to perform their action. Because there is a logical explanation for those functions to be belong to the class, and not to a specific instance of it (you can call the same method with different parameters, and get the desired result, independently of the current object state), you can declare those method as static methods.

[Read more about `static`][1]


  [1]: https://www.learncpp.com/cpp-tutorial/812-static-member-functions/


-----

&lt;h2&gt;Edit:&lt;/h2&gt;
One more mistake that I just noticed in, is that your definition of the function `operation` is: `void operation(char sign, int num1, int den1, int num2, int den2)`, which means that it is not belong to the class, and the definition of this function that does belong to the class is doing nothing:

    void rational::operation(char sign, int num1, int den1, int num2, int den2) {
}

Remove the `void operation(char sign, int num1, int den1, int num2, int den2)` definition, and move the content into the class&#39;s function definition that mentioned above.

